{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584915"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14833"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14833"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.37,0.12,0.39,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7524"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96893"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18558"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18562"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with easy bruising and prolonged bleeding after minor cuts over the past few months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Laboratory investigations reveal a prolonged prothrombin time and activated partial thromboplastin time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is activated by both Factor Xa and thrombin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor XII","Factor I","Factor VII","Factor V","Factor III"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V\u003C/strong\u003E plays a central role in coagulation through its activation by both Factor Xa and thrombin. Once activated, Factor V serves as an essential cofactor in the prothrombinase complex (Factor Xa/Va) which dramatically accelerates the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor XII\u003C/strong\u003E (Hageman factor) is activated by contact with negatively charged surfaces, initiating the intrinsic pathway. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor I\u003C/strong\u003E (fibrinogen) is cleaved by thrombin to form fibrin monomers. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VII\u003C/strong\u003E is activated by tissue factor (Factor III) to initiate the extrinsic pathway. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor III\u003C/strong\u003E (tissue factor) is a cellular receptor that becomes exposed upon vessel injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dual activation of Factor V by both Factor Xa and thrombin represents an important positive feedback loop in coagulation. This feedback amplifies thrombin generation, as activated Factor V enhances the production of more thrombin, which in turn activates more Factor V.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Factor V is activated by both Factor Xa and thrombin, playing a crucial role in the coagulation cascade.","The activation of Factor V by thrombin is an example of positive feedback in the coagulation process.","Factor V acts as a cofactor for Factor Xa in the prothrombinase complex, which converts prothrombin to thrombin."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","Chaudhry R, Usama SM, Babiker HM. Physiology, Coagulation Pathways. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482253/","Al-Amer OM. The role of thrombin in haemostasis. Blood Coagul Fibrinolysis. 2022 Apr 1;33(3):145-148. doi: 10.1097/MBC.0000000000001130. Epub 2022 Mar 2. PMID: 35239615."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21127"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21127"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TJxMctxGJTgnip6K0gO9SaoXQBMXR1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TJxMctxGJTgnip6K0gO9SaoXQBMXR1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":1400}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T12:20:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T12:20:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null